  "text": "Although a diagnostic classification approach has been the predominant approach in quantitative epidemiological studies of aversive emotional states in NICU mothers, an early phenomenological study of women's experiences with postpartum depression recognized that at the heart of this disorder lie symptoms of depression and anxiety [CITATION_1] . In an aptly titled publication, The Many Faces of Postpartum Depression, the authors notes: ''not every mother suffering from postpartum depression will present with the same constellation of symptoms'' (Beck & Indman, 2005, p. 573) . This multifaceted conceptualization of postpartum depression aligns with the common factor conceptual framework (see Figure 1B ).",
